Resource extraction was covered in Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.
Environmental contamination is discussed in this chapter.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Contamination intensity of resource extraction}
\label{sec:contamination_intensity}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The contamination intensity of resource extraction ($C$)
represents the amount of environmental contamination (emitted wastes)
per unit of extracted and consumed resources (ingested materials).
Examples of environmental contamination include
water eutrophication (from fertilizer runoff),
SO$_2$ emissions (from burning sulfurous coal),
CO$_2$ emissions (from burning fossil fuels),
desertification (due to overcultivation of crops, overgrazing of livestock, and alien species invasion), and
species loss (due to habitat loss, environmental toxins, and over-exploitation).
With reference to a few of the critical materials in Table~\ref{tab:CRMs},
specific examples of the environmental contamination caused by resource extraction and consumption include:
%
\begin{itemize}

  \item air, water, and soil pollution~\cite{Lee:2017ui} (environmental contamination) in the form of
        bauxite dust,
        sulfur dioxide (SO$_2$), and
        nitrous oxides (NO$_\mathrm{x}$) emissions
        from bauxite mining (material extraction),

  \item Toxic tailings (environmental contamination)
        from Tungsten (material extraction)
        mining operations~\cite{Lee:2021tz}, and

  \item Deforestation and reduced forest quality~\cite{Kissinger:2020ut} (environmental contamination)
        to make way for rubber plantations (material extraction)
        in southeast Asia.

\end{itemize}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Prime example: carbon intensity of energy}
\label{sec:carbon_intensity_of_energy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

In this book,
energy is the prime example of material extraction and consumption,
as discussed in Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.
Because CO$_2$ emissions are a significant source of environmental contamination
coming from energy consumption,
it follows that the prime example of environmental contamination
is CO$_2$ emissions.
Thus, the prime example for contamination intensity ($C$) is the CO$_2$ intensity of energy.
The units for the CO$_2$ intensity of energy are,
e.g., tonnes of CO$_2$ emitted per MJ of energy consumed.

Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_CO2_sankey} shows sources of CO$_2$ emissions from the U.S.\ economy in 2018.
However, CO$_2$ emissions from electricity generatation are not attributed to end uses for electricity
in Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_CO2_sankey}.
Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions} shows the result of attributing CO$_2$ emissions to end uses,
thereby completing the picture of U.S.\ carbon emissions.
Attributing CO$_2$ emissions from electricity generation significantly increases the share of CO$_2$
emissions from the Residential and Commercial sectors.

