\section{Reducing the carbon intensity of energy}
\label{sec:reducing_c}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC} shows that reducing any of the right-hand side terms to 0
will eliminate CO$_2$ emissions.
I.e., if population ($P$), affluence ($A$), energy intensity of the economy ($I_p$)
or carbon intensity of energy ($C$) go to 0,
CO$_2$ emissions will be eliminated.
Few people want to reduce population ($P$) or affluence ($A$).
The primary energy intensity of the economy ($I_p$) has been declining
since 1960 (Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph}),
but not as fast as population (Figure~\ref{fig:PopulationGraph})
and affluence (Figure~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph}) are growing.

Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonIntensityGraph} shows that the carbon intensity of energy
has hovered around 63 Mt CO$_2$/EJ from 1960 to today.
Thus, for the last 60 years, the carbon intensity of energy has been stubbornly constant.
It appears that eliminating CO$_2$ emissions by significantly reducing
the carbon intensity of energy ($C$) will be require unprecedented changes
to the world's primary energy sources.

If we want to reduce CO$_2$ emissions by reducing
the carbon intensity of energy ($C$),
we could transition back to the energy mix of the first half of the 18$^\mathrm{th}$ century,
exclusive use of traditional biofuels, namely wood and wood products.
(See Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}.)
However, supplying the energy needs of today's economy would be impossible:
we don't have enough available land area to grow the required amount of crops.
**** Josh should make a calculation to verify this claim. ****

Alternatively, we could transition the world energy system
to renewable energy sources: water (hydro), wind, and solar (WWS).
**** Add reference to Dellucci here. ****
However, in addition to changing the world's energy sources,
reducing the carbon intensity of energy
will require
significant changes to the world's energy infrastructure.
Indeed, a transition to WWS will bring several new challenges.
First, WWS energy resources produce electricity, not liquid fuels.
Thus, any economic sector that currently relies upon liquid fuels must be electrified.
An important example of the need to electrify is the transportation sector.
Today, transport is almost exclusively powered by liquid fossil fuels (gasoline and diesel).
Electrifying the world's transportation fleet is a prerequisite to a transition to WWS
and a zero-carbon economy.
Electrification of the world's transportation fleet will be very expensive.
**** Josh to find a cost estimate. ****

Second, wind and solar (the \emph{WS} in W\emph{WS}) are intermittent sources of electricity,
while coal, natural gas, nuclear, and water (hydro) sources are not.
At present, electric grids accommodate only a fraction of intermittent electricity, much less than 100\%.
So a transition to wind and solar primary energy sources will require
redesign and re-implementation of electricity grids worldwide.

Third, WWS primary energy sources are energy intensive to manufacture.
So the transition to a WWS future will require significant energy investment
in addition to significant financial investment.
If the energy to make WWS systems comes from fossil fuels,
significant CO$_2$ will be emitted during the transition
from today's energy regime to a WWS regime.

